post0.caption: Scientists have a promising new idea to defeat the coronavirus. In order to find new treatments for COVID-19, scientists are probing how the coronavirus alters human cells when it infects and hijacks them. Most recently a research team at the Frankfurt University hospital announced theyve identified a number of compounds available in existing drugs including the metabolism-inhibiting cancer medication WP1122 that seem to stop the coronavirus from reproducing inside a host. The teams findings were published on May 14th in the journal Nature. Tap the link in our bio to read more about their research. #coronavirus

post2.caption: Ok UFO hunters, here we go The Pentagon has released new information about a series of fascinating encounters between US Navy pilots and unidentified flying objects. The hazard reports include details about the size and shape of the unidentified aerial phenomena. It's an interesting twist after decades of denial from the US government. To be clear, the Pentagon confirming authentic UFO videos doesn't necessarily mean we've found aliens, but it does mean that we don't really have an explanation for these flying objects in the footage, hence UFO. While unusual aircraft can't be ruled out, it's entirely possible the objects seen in Navy videos might be drones, although no nearby drone operators could be located. Tap the link in our bio to read more about what the Pentagon had to say about these UFOs. #UFO

post1.caption: Apple has filed regulatory documents with the Federal Communications Commission for a low-power network adapter that it says is intended for internal use only. The filing, published during a routine update of the FCC's database, covers a low-power Wi-Fi transmitter that operates below 1 GHz. In practical terms, that likely means use of the 802.11ah protocol used for Internet of Things applications. While most of the documents in the filing are concealed under a confidentiality agreement, a regulatory label reveals the codename "Meerkat" and a model number of A2282. Neither the codename nor the product number are currently associated with a released Apple product. Full story link in our bio

post2.caption: While other children in the US were having full classroom lessons on Zoom, Juana spent the first month of quarantine just practicing the alphabet and learning to count in Spanish. Until recently, the kindergartner was one of 1.2 million students in California who lack access to a device or the internet. Across the country, around 42 million Americans do not have access to broadband internetand 1 in 10 Americans have access to the internet only via their smartphones. Were going to see a widening of educational inequality that will last a long time and wont fade away, says a Harvard professor who studies how access to the internet affects inequality. He fears the current disruption will have a permanent effect on the poorer students. Click the link in our bio to learn more about the children being left behind by America's online schooling.
